The Safety Lifecycle in ISO 26262 is the structured process that ensures functional safety throughout the entire product life. It consists of multiple phases:

âœ… Phases of Safety Lifecycle
	1. Concept Phase
		â—‹ Item Definition
		â—‹ Hazard Analysis and Risk Assessment (HARA)
		â—‹ Define Safety Goals and ASIL
	2. System Level Development
		â—‹ Derive Functional Safety Requirements
		â—‹ Allocate requirements to hardware and software
	3. Hardware Development
		â—‹ Technical safety requirements for hardware
		â—‹ Hardware design and verification
	4. Software Development
		â—‹ Technical safety requirements for software
		â—‹ Software design, coding, and verification
	5. Integration and Testing
		â—‹ Hardware-software integration
		â—‹ System-level safety validation
	6. Production and Operation
		â—‹ Ensure safety during manufacturing and field use
		â—‹ Maintenance and service considerations
	7. Decommissioning
		â—‹ Safe disposal or recycling of components

âœ… Start and End Points
	â€¢ Start: Concept Phase (Item Definition + HARA)
	â€¢ End: Decommissioning after product life

Interview Tip: 
	â€œThe safety lifecycle starts with defining the item and performing HARA to set safety goals and ASIL. It ends after decommissioning, ensuring safety is maintained from design to disposal.â€

âœ… Starting Point of Safety Lifecycle
The starting point is the Concept Phase, specifically:
	â€¢ Item Definition: Define the system or function under consideration.
	â€¢ HARA (Hazard Analysis and Risk Assessment): Identify hazards, assess risk, and determine ASIL.
	â€¢ Safety Goals: High-level objectives derived from HARA.
This phase sets the foundation for all subsequent safety activities.

âœ… Ending Point of Safety Lifecycle
The ending point is after:
	â€¢ Production, Operation, and Service: Ensure safety during manufacturing and field use.
	â€¢ Decommissioning: Safe disposal or recycling of components.
ISO 26262 requires safety to be maintained throughout the entire product life, not just development.

âœ… Flow Summary
Start â†’ Concept Phase (HARA, Safety Goals) â†’ System Design â†’ HW/SW Development â†’ Integration & Testing â†’ Production & Operation â†’ Decommissioning â†’ End

