13. Unit Verification Methods in ISO 26262

Common Unit Verification Methods
	1. Static Analysis
		â—‹ Examines code without executing it.
		â—‹ Detects syntax errors, coding guideline violations (e.g., MISRA), and potential runtime issues.
		â—‹ Tools: Polyspace, QAC.
	2. Code Reviews / Inspections
		â—‹ Manual or semi-automated review of source code.
		â—‹ Ensures adherence to design and safety principles.
	3. Dynamic Analysis
		â—‹ Executes the unit in a controlled environment.
		â—‹ Checks runtime behavior, memory usage, and timing.
	4. Unit Testing
		â—‹ Tests individual units with test cases derived from requirements.
		â—‹ Includes white-box testing for coverage and black-box testing for functionality.
	5. Fault Injection
		â—‹ Introduces faults deliberately to verify robustness and error handling.
	6. Formal Verification
		â—‹ Mathematical proof that the unit satisfies its specification.
		â—‹ Used for high-ASIL components.
	7. Interface Testing
		â—‹ Verifies correct interaction between the unit and its environment (inputs/outputs).

Coverage Requirements by ASIL
	â€¢ ASIL A/B: Statement and branch coverage.
	â€¢ ASIL C/D: Modified Condition/Decision Coverage (MC/DC).
Interview Tip: Explain how these methods validate implementation against requirements.

14. Unit Test Derivation Methods in ISO 26262
1. Requirements-Based Testing
	â—‹ Test cases derived directly from software unit requirements.
	â—‹ Ensures each requirement is verified.
	â—‹ Example: If a requirement says â€œADC shall detect over-temperature at 120Â°C,â€ create a test case for 120Â°C threshold.
2. Structure-Based Testing (White-Box)
	â—‹ Based on code structure.
	â—‹ Targets coverage metrics: 
		Â§ Statement Coverage
		Â§ Branch Coverage
		Â§ MC/DC (Modified Condition/Decision Coverage) for ASIL C/D.
	â—‹ Example: Test all branches of an if-else condition.
3. Interface Testing
	â—‹ Tests input/output interfaces of the unit.
	â—‹ Ensures correct data exchange and error handling.
	â—‹ Example: Validate CAN message parsing in a communication unit.
4. Fault Injection Testing
	â—‹ Introduces faults to verify robustness and safety mechanisms.
	â—‹ Example: Inject invalid sensor data and check error handling.
5. Equivalence Class Partitioning
	â—‹ Divide input domain into valid and invalid classes.
	â—‹ Test representative values from each class.
	â—‹ Example: For speed input (0â€“200 km/h), test 0, 100, 200, and out-of-range values.
6. Boundary Value Analysis
	â—‹ Focus on edge cases near limits.
	â—‹ Example: Test temperature at 119Â°C, 120Â°C, and 121Â°C for threshold logic.
7. Error Guessing
	â—‹ Based on experience to guess likely error-prone areas.
	â—‹ Example: Test null pointers or uninitialized variables.

ASIL Considerations
â€¢ ASIL A/B: Requirements-based + basic structural coverage.
â€¢ ASIL C/D: Requirements-based + MC/DC + fault injection + robustness tests.
Interview Tip: Emphasize traceability to safety requirements.

15. Coverage Metrics for Unit Test in ISO 26262
â€¢ Statement Coverage
	â€¢ Ensures every executable statement is executed at least once.
	â€¢ ASIL A/B: Recommended minimum metric.
	â€¢ Example: If code has 100 statements, all must be executed during tests.
â€¢ Branch Coverage
	â€¢ Ensures every branch (true/false path of decisions) is executed.
	â€¢ ASIL B/C: Strongly recommended.
	â€¢ Example: For if (x > 0), both true and false paths must be tested.
â€¢ Modified Condition/Decision Coverage (MC/DC)
	â€¢ Ensures each condition in a decision independently affects the outcome.
	â€¢ ASIL C/D: Mandatory for high safety levels.
	â€¢ Example: For if (A && B), test cases must show A and B independently influencing the result.
â€¢ Function Coverage
	â€¢ Verifies that all functions are called during testing.
	â€¢ Common for all ASIL levels.
â€¢ Call Coverage
	â€¢ Ensures all function calls and call sequences are tested.
	â€¢ Important for complex software architectures.
â€¢ Data Flow Coverage
	â€¢ Tracks variable definitions and uses.
	â€¢ Recommended for ASIL C/D for robustness.
Interview Tip: MC/DC is mandatory for ASIL D software.

16. Integration Verification Methods in ISO 26262
	â€¢ I
	Main Integration Verification Methods
		1. Requirements-Based Integration Testing
			â—‹ Verifies that integrated components meet software architectural requirements.
			â—‹ Example: Check if ADC driver and DTC module interact correctly for temperature fault detection.
		2. Interface Testing
			â—‹ Tests data exchange and control flow between integrated units.
			â—‹ Example: Validate CAN communication between ECU modules.
		3. Functional Testing
			â—‹ Ensures integrated functionality behaves as expected.
			â—‹ Example: Verify torque calculation after integrating motor control and sensor modules.
		4. Fault Injection Testing
			â—‹ Introduces faults at integration points to test error handling and safety mechanisms.
			â—‹ Example: Inject corrupted CAN frames and check system response.
		5. Stress and Load Testing
			â—‹ Tests system under high load or extreme conditions.
			â—‹ Example: Validate timing behavior when multiple tasks run concurrently.
		6. Dynamic Analysis
			â—‹ Observes runtime behavior of integrated components.
			â—‹ Example: Memory usage and timing analysis during integration.
		7. Back-to-Back Testing
			â—‹ Compares results between model-based simulation and actual integrated implementation.
			â—‹ Example: Compare Simulink model outputs with integrated ECU outputs.
		8. Hardware-in-the-Loop (HIL) Testing
			â—‹ Uses real hardware with simulated environment to verify integration.
			â—‹ Example: Test ECU with simulated vehicle dynamics.
	â€¢ Interview Tip: Mention how integration ensures correct interaction between components.

