18. Coverage Metrics for Integration Test in ISO 26262
Key Coverage Metrics
	1. Interface Coverage
		â—‹ Ensures all interfaces between software units/components are exercised.
		â—‹ Example: Every CAN message interface between communication stack and application layer is tested.
	2. Functional Coverage
		â—‹ Verifies that all functional requirements for integrated components are tested.
		â—‹ Example: All torque calculation scenarios after integrating motor control and sensor modules.
	3. Data Flow Coverage
		â—‹ Ensures all data paths between components are tested.
		â—‹ Example: Sensor data flow through ADC â†’ signal processing â†’ application logic.
	4. Control Flow Coverage
		â—‹ Tests all control paths across integrated modules.
		â—‹ Example: Validate all execution paths in task scheduling and interrupt handling.
	5. Scenario Coverage
		â—‹ Ensures all operational scenarios are tested.
		â—‹ Example: Vehicle start-up, braking, and emergency shutdown scenarios.
	6. Fault Injection Coverage
		â—‹ Measures how many fault scenarios at integration points are tested.
		â—‹ Example: Inject corrupted CAN frames, invalid sensor data, and check system response.
	7. Boundary Value Coverage
		â—‹ Tests edge cases for integrated components.
		â—‹ Example: Maximum and minimum sensor values across integrated modules.

Interview Tip: Explain how these metrics ensure completeness of integration testing.



âœ… How HARA is Performed at Vehicle Level
HARA (Hazard Analysis and Risk Assessment) is done early in the Concept Phase of ISO 26262 at the vehicle level to identify hazards and assess their risk.
Steps:
	1. Identify Item
Define the system or function (e.g., braking system, steering system).
	2. Identify Hazards
List potential hazardous events (e.g., unintended acceleration, loss of braking).
	3. Define Operational Situations
Consider different driving scenarios (city, highway, parking).
	4. Assess Risk Using S-E-C 
		â—‹ Severity (S): Impact on life (S0â€“S3)
		â—‹ Exposure (E): Frequency of situation (E0â€“E4)
		â—‹ Controllability (C): Driverâ€™s ability to control (C0â€“C3)
	5. Determine ASIL
Use ISO 26262 risk matrix to assign ASIL (QM, A, B, C, D).
	6. Define Safety Goals
High-level objectives to prevent hazards (e.g., â€œPrevent unintended accelerationâ€).

âœ… How It Drives the Safety Lifecycle
	â€¢ Safety Goals â†’ Functional Safety Requirements â†’ Technical Safety Requirements â†’ HW/SW Requirements
	â€¢ ASIL influences:
		â—‹ Design rigor (higher ASIL = stricter design)
		â—‹ Verification methods (e.g., MC/DC for ASIL D)
		â—‹ Safety mechanisms (redundancy, monitoring)
	â€¢ Traceability from vehicle-level hazards down to component-level implementation.

Interview Tip: 
	â€œHARA at the vehicle level identifies hazards and assigns ASIL, which drives the entire safety lifecycle by defining safety goals and influencing design, verification, and validation activities.â€
	
	

Static Analysis and Dynamic Analysis in the context of ISO 26262 and software verification:

âœ… Static Analysis
	â€¢ Definition: Examination of code without executing it.
	â€¢ Purpose: Detect coding errors, violations of coding standards, and potential safety issues early.
	â€¢ Methods:
		â—‹ Manual Code Review
		â—‹ Tool-based Analysis (e.g., Polyspace, QAC)
	â€¢ Checks:
		â—‹ Data flow anomalies
		â—‹ Dead code
		â—‹ MISRA compliance
	â€¢ Advantages:
		â—‹ Performed early in development
		â—‹ No need for test cases or hardware
	â€¢ ISO 26262 Use:
		â—‹ Recommended for all ASIL levels
		â—‹ Mandatory for higher ASIL (C/D)

âœ… Dynamic Analysis
	â€¢ Definition: Examination of software during execution.
	â€¢ Purpose: Validate runtime behavior and detect issues like memory leaks, timing violations.
	â€¢ Methods:
		â—‹ Unit Testing
		â—‹ Integration Testing
		â—‹ Hardware-in-the-Loop (HIL)
	â€¢ Checks:
		â—‹ Functional correctness
		â—‹ Performance under real conditions
	â€¢ Advantages:
		â—‹ Confirms actual behavior on target hardware
	â€¢ ISO 26262 Use:
		â—‹ Essential for verifying safety requirements at runtime

Interview Tip: 
	â€œStatic analysis checks code without execution, focusing on structure and compliance, while dynamic analysis validates runtime behavior. Both are complementary and required for ISO 26262 compliance.â€


Q.what are the unit verification methods defined in ISO 26262.
	
	In ISO 26262, unit verification methods are techniques used to verify the correctness of individual software units (functions, modules, or classes) during the Software Unit Verification phase (Part 6, Clause 9). These methods ensure that each unit behaves as intended and meets its safety requirements.
	
ğŸ” ASIL Level Impact
ASIL Level	Recommended Rigor
ASIL A	Basic methods like unit testing and code review
ASIL B	Add static analysis and coverage
ASIL C/D	Require formal methods, fault injection, MC/DC coverage, and independence in verification

ğŸ”· What is MC/DC Coverage?
MC/DC stands for Modified Condition/Decision Coverage. It is a code coverage metric used in safety-critical software development, especially in ISO 26262 and DO-178C (aviation). It ensures that each condition within a decision is tested independently to verify its impact on the decision outcome.

âœ… Why Is MC/DC Important?
	â€¢ Required for ASIL D level software in ISO 26262.
	â€¢ Ensures high confidence in logic correctness.
	â€¢ Detects hidden logical errors that simpler coverage metrics (like statement or branch coverage) may miss.

ğŸ” MC/DC Coverage Criteria
To achieve MC/DC, your test cases must satisfy:
	1. Each condition in a decision must be evaluated to true and false.
	2. Each condition must independently affect the decisionâ€™s outcome.
	3. All possible outcomes of the decision must be tested.



ğŸ”· Coverage Metrics Defined in ISO 26262 (Part 6, Clause 9)
âœ… 1. Statement Coverage
	â€¢ Measures whether each line of code has been executed at least once.
	â€¢ Goal: Ensure all code is reachable and tested.
	â€¢ Example: If a function has 10 lines, and 8 are executed during tests â†’ 80% statement coverage.

âœ… 2. Branch Coverage
	â€¢ Measures whether each branch of control structures (if, else, switch, case) has been executed.
	â€¢ Goal: Ensure all decision paths are tested.
	â€¢ Example: For if (x > 0), test both true and false paths.

âœ… 3. Modified Condition/Decision Coverage (MC/DC)
	â€¢ Measures whether each condition in a decision has been tested independently to affect the outcome.
	â€¢ Goal: Ensure logical correctness of complex decisions.
	â€¢ Required for: ASIL D
	â€¢ Example: For if (A && B), test cases must show how changing A or B alone affects the result.

âœ… 4. Function Coverage (optional but useful)
	â€¢ Measures whether each function or method has been called during testing.
	â€¢ Helps ensure all units are exercised.

ğŸ” ASIL Level Requirements
Coverage Metric	ASIL A	ASIL B	ASIL C	ASIL D
Statement Coverage	âœ…	âœ…	âœ…	âœ…
Branch Coverage	Optional	âœ…	âœ…	âœ…
MC/DC Coverage	âŒ	Optional	âœ…	âœ…

ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview (with Example)
	â€œIn ISO 26262, unit testing must meet specific coverage metrics based on ASIL level. For ASIL D, we used MC/DC coverage to verify that each condition in our decision logic independently affects the outcome. For example, in a derating function with logic if (temp > threshold && sensorOK), we created test cases to toggle each condition separately. We used RapiCover to measure MC/DC and GTest for unit execution. This ensured compliance with ISO 26262 Part 6.â€
	
	
	
	ğŸ”· What is Code Coverage?
	Code coverage is a software testing metric that measures how much of the source code is executed during testing. It helps assess the effectiveness of test cases and ensures that critical parts of the code are not left untested â€” especially important in safety-critical systems like automotive software under ISO 26262.
	
	âœ… Why Is Code Coverage Important?
		â€¢ Ensures quality and completeness of testing.
		â€¢ Helps identify untested or unreachable code.
		â€¢ Required for ASIL C/D levels in ISO 26262.
		â€¢ Supports confidence in software correctness.
	
	
	
	ğŸ”· Unit Test Derivation Methods Defined in ISO 26262 (Part 6, Clause 9)
	ISO 26262 recommends several test design techniques to derive meaningful and safety-relevant unit test cases. These methods are especially important for ASIL C and ASIL D levels.
	
	âœ… 1. Equivalence Class Partitioning
		â€¢ Purpose: Divide input data into groups (classes) where the system behaves similarly.
		â€¢ Example: For a function that accepts temperature from -40Â°C to 125Â°C:
			â—‹ Valid class: [-40 to 125]
			â—‹ Invalid class: < -40, > 125
		â€¢ Test Case: Pick one value from each class (e.g., -50, 25, 130).
	
	âœ… 2. Boundary Value Analysis
		â€¢ Purpose: Test values at the edges of input ranges, where errors often occur.
		â€¢ Example: For range 0 to 100, test:
			â—‹ 0, 1, 99, 100, 101
		â€¢ Test Case: Validate how the unit handles edge cases.
	
	âœ… 3. Error Guessing
		â€¢ Purpose: Use experience to guess likely error-prone inputs.
		â€¢ Example: Pass NULL pointer, divide by zero, or invalid enum values.
		â€¢ Test Case: readADC(NULL) or calculateSpeed(0, time=0)
	
	âœ… 4. Decision Table Testing
		â€¢ Purpose: Create a table of conditions and actions to cover all combinations.
		â€¢ Example: For a derating logic:
			â—‹ Conditions: temp > threshold, sensorOK
			â—‹ Actions: applyDerating, logFault
		â€¢ Test Case: Cover all combinations of true/false for conditions.
	
	âœ… 5. State-Based Testing
		â€¢ Purpose: Test transitions between states in a state machine.
		â€¢ Example: DTC states: Monitor â†’ Pending â†’ Confirmed â†’ Cleared
		â€¢ Test Case: Trigger transitions with fault injection and recovery.
	
	âœ… 6. MC/DC-Based Test Derivation
		â€¢ Purpose: Derive test cases to achieve Modified Condition/Decision Coverage.
		â€¢ Example: For if (A && B), create tests to toggle A and B independently.
		â€¢ Test Case: A=true/B=true, A=false/B=true, A=true/B=false
	
	ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview
		â€œIn ISO 26262, unit test derivation methods help us design effective test cases for safety-critical software. For example, in my ADC driver, I used boundary value analysis to test extreme voltages, and equivalence partitioning to group valid and invalid ranges. For ASIL D logic, I applied MC/DC-based derivation to ensure each condition in decisions was independently tested. 
		
		
ğŸ”· What is Meant by a Safety Mechanism in ISO 26262?
A safety mechanism is a technical solution or feature implemented in hardware or software to detect, prevent, or mitigate faults that could lead to hazardous events in a safety-critical system. These mechanisms are essential to achieve or maintain functional safety, especially in automotive systems.

Key Characteristics
â€¢ Technical Implementation: They are tangible features integrated directly into the system's design (hardware and software levels).
â€¢ Fault Management: They address both random hardware failures and systematic failures, aiming to detect faults when they occur and initiate a proper reaction.
â€¢ Achieving or Maintaining a Safe State: In the event of a detected fault, a safety mechanism ensures the system transitions to a pre-defined "safe state" where no harm can occur (e.g., a limp-home mode for an engine or engaging emergency brakes).
â€¢ Timely Response: The mechanism must act within a specified Fault Tolerant Time Interval (FTTI) from the fault's occurrence to prevent a hazardous event.


âœ… Purpose of Safety Mechanisms
	â€¢ Detect faults (e.g., sensor failure, software crash)
	â€¢ Prevent hazards (e.g., unintended acceleration, overheating)
	â€¢ Mitigate consequences (e.g., reduce power, activate fallback mode)
	â€¢ Achieve ASIL goals (Automotive Safety Integrity Level)



âœ… Integration Verification Methods Defined in ISO 26262
ğŸ”¹ 1. Interface Testing
	â€¢ Purpose: Verify that components exchange data correctly through defined interfaces.
	â€¢ Example: Check that an SWC sends correct CAN signals to another SWC via RTE.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Data Flow Analysis
	â€¢ Purpose: Ensure data is transmitted and transformed correctly across components.
	â€¢ Example: Validate that ADC raw values are correctly passed to temperature monitoring logic.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Control Flow Analysis
	â€¢ Purpose: Verify correct sequence of function calls and state transitions during integration.
	â€¢ Example: Ensure derating logic executes only after sensor validation.

ğŸ”¹ 4. Integration Testing with Stimulus/Response
	â€¢ Purpose: Apply input stimuli and check system response at integration level.
	â€¢ Example: Inject high temperature input and verify power reduction occurs.

ğŸ”¹ 5. Fault Injection Testing
	â€¢ Purpose: Introduce faults at integration points to verify robustness and error handling.
	â€¢ Example: Simulate CAN message loss and check fallback mechanism.

ğŸ”¹ 6. Back-to-Back Testing
	â€¢ Purpose: Compare results between model-based design (e.g., Simulink) and actual integrated code.
	â€¢ Example: Validate that ECU implementation matches MATLAB model outputs.

ğŸ”¹ 7. Resource Usage Verification
	â€¢ Purpose: Check memory, CPU load, and timing constraints during integration.
	â€¢ Example: Ensure integrated SWCs do not exceed stack limits or violate real-time deadlines.

ğŸ” ASIL Impact
	â€¢ ASIL A/B: Basic interface and functional integration tests.
	â€¢ ASIL C/D: Add fault injection, timing analysis, and independence in verification.

ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview
	â€œIntegration verification ensures that software units and components interact correctly. In my project, we used interface testing to validate RTE communication between SWCs, fault injection to check robustness under CAN message loss, and timing analysis to ensure real-time performance. These methods are recommended by ISO 26262 for SWE.5 and SYS.3 phases.â€



âœ… Coverage Metrics for Integration Testing (ISO 26262 Part 6, Clause 10)
Unlike unit testing (which focuses on code-level coverage like statement, branch, and MC/DC), integration testing focuses on interface and interaction coverage. The main metrics are:

ğŸ”¹ 1. Interface Coverage
	â€¢ Definition: Measures whether all interfaces between software units/components have been exercised during tests.
	â€¢ Example: If SWC SensorManager communicates with DeratingController via RTE ports, all signals and ports must be tested.

ğŸ”¹ 2. Data Flow Coverage
	â€¢ Definition: Ensures that all data exchanged between components is tested for correctness.
	â€¢ Example: Validate that ADC raw values flow correctly to temperature monitoring logic and then to derating logic.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Control Flow Coverage
	â€¢ Definition: Measures whether all control paths between integrated components are executed.
	â€¢ Example: Check that the sequence of calls from readADC() â†’ filterValue() â†’ applyDerating() occurs correctly.

ğŸ”¹ 4. Fault Injection Coverage
	â€¢ Definition: Verifies that error handling paths are tested when faults occur at integration points.
	â€¢ Example: Simulate CAN message loss and confirm fallback mechanism activates.

ğŸ”¹ 5. Requirement-to-Test Coverage
	â€¢ Definition: Ensures that all integration-level requirements have corresponding test cases and are verified.
	â€¢ Example: If requirement says â€œTemperature derating shall activate within 100 ms,â€ integration tests must validate timing.

ğŸ” ASIL Level Impact
	â€¢ ASIL A/B: Basic interface and functional coverage.
	â€¢ ASIL C/D: Add fault injection, timing analysis, and independence in verification.

ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview
	â€œIntegration coverage in ISO 26262 focuses on interfaces and interactions rather than individual statements. For example, in my project, we measured interface coverage to ensure all RTE ports between SWCs were tested, data flow coverage to validate ADC values propagate correctly, and fault injection coverage to check robustness under CAN message loss. These metrics help ensure safety compliance at the integration level.â€

ğŸ”· What is Top-Down Safety Analysis?
Top-down safety analysis is a deductive approach used in ISO 26262 and other safety standards to identify potential causes of system-level hazards. It starts from a known hazard or safety goal and works downward to find possible faults or failures that could lead to that hazard.

âœ… Key Characteristics:
	â€¢ Starts from hazards or safety goals.
	â€¢ Used in Hazard Analysis and Risk Assessment (HARA).
	â€¢ Helps define functional and technical safety requirements.
	â€¢ Common methods:
		â—‹ Fault Tree Analysis (FTA)
		â—‹ Failure Mode Effects and Diagnostic Analysis (FMEDA)

ğŸ“Œ Example:
	Hazard: Unintended acceleration
	Safety Goal: Prevent unintended acceleration
	Top-down analysis identifies possible causes:
		â—‹ Faulty throttle sensor
		â—‹ Software logic error
		â—‹ CAN communication failure
These causes are traced down to hardware/software faults, and safety mechanisms are defined to mitigate them.

ğŸ”· What is Bottom-Up Safety Analysis?
Bottom-up safety analysis is an inductive approach that starts from individual component failures and analyzes their potential impact on the system. It helps identify unexpected failure propagation and ensures that low-level faults donâ€™t lead to hazards.

âœ… Key Characteristics:
	â€¢ Starts from component-level faults.
	â€¢ Used in detailed design and implementation phases.
	â€¢ Helps verify safety mechanisms and fault containment.
	â€¢ Common methods:
		â—‹ Failure Mode and Effects Analysis (FMEA)
		â—‹ Dependent Failure Analysis (DFA)

ğŸ“Œ Example:
	Fault: ADC channel stuck at max value
	Bottom-up analysis checks:
		â—‹ Impact on temperature monitoring
		â—‹ Whether derating logic is triggered incorrectly
		â—‹ Whether system enters safe state
This helps ensure that faults are detected and mitigated locally, without affecting overall system safety.

ğŸ” Summary Table
Aspect	Top-Down Safety Analysis	Bottom-Up Safety Analysis
Approach	Deductive	Inductive
Starts From	Hazard or safety goal	Component-level fault
Purpose	Identify causes of hazards	Assess impact of faults
Used In	HARA, safety requirement derivation	Design, implementation, verification
Methods	FTA, FMEDA	FMEA, DFA

ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview
	â€œTop-down safety analysis starts from a known hazard and traces possible causes. For example, to prevent unintended acceleration, we analyzed faults in throttle sensors and software logic. Bottom-up analysis starts from faults like ADC failure and checks their impact on system behavior. We used FMEA to ensure that such faults donâ€™t lead to unsafe states. Both approaches are essential in ISO 26262 to ensure complete safety coverage.â€



Hereâ€™s a detailed explanation of HARA, FMEA, and DFA safety analyses, including their purpose, process, and outputs:

âœ… 1. HARA (Hazard Analysis and Risk Assessment)
What is HARA?
HARA is the starting point of ISO 26262 safety lifecycle. It identifies potential hazards in the system, evaluates their risk, and assigns an ASIL (Automotive Safety Integrity Level).
Purpose
	â€¢ Identify hazards that could lead to unsafe situations.
	â€¢ Assess severity, exposure, and controllability.
	â€¢ Define Safety Goals and assign ASIL.
Process
	1. Identify hazardous events (e.g., unintended acceleration).
	2. Assess:
		â—‹ Severity (S): Impact on occupants (S0â€“S3).
		â—‹ Exposure (E): Probability of occurrence (E0â€“E4).
		â—‹ Controllability (C): Driverâ€™s ability to control (C0â€“C3).
	3. Determine ASIL (Aâ€“D) based on S, E, C.
Outputs
	â€¢ List of hazards and hazardous events.
	â€¢ ASIL classification for each hazard.
	â€¢ Safety Goals (e.g., â€œPrevent unintended accelerationâ€).
	â€¢ Basis for Functional Safety Concept.

âœ… 2. FMEA (Failure Mode and Effects Analysis)
What is FMEA?
FMEA is a bottom-up safety analysis method. It starts from component-level failures and analyzes their effects on the system.
Purpose
	â€¢ Identify failure modes of components.
	â€¢ Assess effects on system and safety goals.
	â€¢ Define diagnostic coverage and safety mechanisms.
Process
	1. List components and their possible failure modes (e.g., ADC stuck at max value).
	2. Analyze effects on higher-level functions.
	3. Assign severity, occurrence, detection ratings.
	4. Calculate Risk Priority Number (RPN).
	5. Define mitigation actions.
Outputs
	â€¢ FMEA table with:
		â—‹ Failure modes
		â—‹ Effects
		â—‹ Severity, occurrence, detection ratings
	â€¢ Recommended safety mechanisms (e.g., range checks, redundancy).
	â€¢ Diagnostic coverage metrics.

âœ… 3. DFA (Dependent Failure Analysis)
What is DFA?
DFA checks for dependent failures that could compromise independence between safety mechanisms or redundant elements.
Purpose
	â€¢ Ensure ASIL decomposition independence.
	â€¢ Identify common cause failures (e.g., same power supply for redundant sensors).
	â€¢ Verify freedom from interference.
Process
	1. Identify redundant elements or safety mechanisms.
	2. Analyze shared resources (power, clock, software).
	3. Assess common cause failure probability.
	4. Define mitigation measures (e.g., separate power rails).
Outputs
	â€¢ DFA report listing:
		â—‹ Dependent failure scenarios
		â—‹ Common cause analysis
	â€¢ Recommendations for design changes to ensure independence.

ğŸ” Summary Table
Analysis	Approach	Purpose	Outputs
HARA	Top-down	Identify hazards & assign ASIL	Hazard list, ASIL, Safety Goals
FMEA	Bottom-up	Analyze component failures	FMEA table, mitigation actions
DFA	Independence check	Ensure freedom from common cause failures	DFA report, design recommendations

ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview:
	â€œHARA is top-down: start from hazards, assign ASIL, and define safety goals. FMEA is bottom-up: start from component failures and analyze their effects. DFA ensures independence between safety mechanisms and checks for common cause failures. For example, in my EV project, we used HARA to identify hazards like unintended acceleration, FMEA to analyze ADC sensor failures, and DFA to ensure redundant sensors had separate power supplies.â€



ğŸ”· V-Model in Safety Development Life Cycle (ISO 26262)
The V-model in ISO 26262 represents the structured development and verification process for safety-critical automotive systems. It ensures that every development activity has a corresponding verification or validation activity, promoting traceability, completeness, and compliance with safety goals.

âœ… Structure of the V-Model
The V-model is divided into two sides:
ğŸ”¹ Left Side â€“ Development Phases
These phases define and refine the system and software:
	1. Item Definition
	2. Hazard Analysis and Risk Assessment (HARA)
	3. Functional Safety Concept
	4. Technical Safety Concept
	5. System Design
	6. Software Safety Requirements (SWE.1)
	7. Software Architecture Design (SWE.2)
	8. Software Detailed Design (SWE.3)
	9. Software Unit Implementation (SWE.4)

ğŸ”¹ Right Side â€“ Verification & Validation Phases
These phases verify that the system meets safety requirements:
	1. Software Unit Verification (SWE.4)
	2. Software Integration Testing (SWE.5)
	3. Software Qualification Testing (SWE.6)
	4. System Integration Testing (SYS.3)
	5. System Qualification Testing (SYS.4)
	6. Functional Safety Validation

ğŸ” Key Concepts in ISO 26262 V-Model
Concept	Description
Bidirectional Traceability	Requirements are traced from definition to implementation and back through testing.
ASIL Allocation	Safety requirements are assigned ASIL levels based on HARA.
Verification & Validation	Each development phase has a corresponding test phase.
Safety Mechanisms	Implemented and verified to mitigate risks identified in HARA.

ğŸ§  How to Explain in Interview
	â€œThe ISO 26262 V-model ensures that every safety requirement is systematically developed and verified. For example, we start with HARA to identify hazards and assign ASIL. Then we define functional and technical safety concepts, followed by software requirements and architecture. Each of these phases has a corresponding verification phase â€” like SWE.1 is verified in SWE.6, and SWE.2 is verified in SWE.5. This structure ensures traceability and compliance with safety goals.â€
	
	
	
	ğŸ”· Left (Development) vs Right (Verification/Validation) â€” Mapping
	Concept & System Levels
	Left Side â€“ Development	Right Side â€“ Verification/Validation	What is Verified
	Item Definition	Functional Safety Validation	The defined item (use cases, operating scenarios) supports real-world safety needs.
	HARA (Hazard Analysis & Risk Assessment)	Functional Safety Validation	Identified hazards and ASILs lead to safety goals that are validated in vehicle/system context.
	Functional Safety Concept (FSC)	Functional Safety Validation	Safety goals and functional safety requirements are validated against intended use & environment.
	Technical Safety Concept (TSC)	SYS.4 â€“ System Qualification Testing	Technical safety requirements at system level are verified/validated on the integrated system.
	System Design / Architecture	SYS.3 â€“ System Integration Testing	Interfaces, behavior and performance of integrated HW/SW at system level.
		Tip to say in interview:
		â€œConcept-phase artifacts like HARA and FSC are validated on the right side via Functional Safety Validation, while TSC and System Architecture are verified by SYS.3 (integration) and SYS.4 (qualification) respectively.â€
	
	Software Levels (SWE.1â€“SWE.4 â†’ SWE.4â€“SWE.6)
	Left Side â€“ Development	Right Side â€“ Verification/Testing	What is Verified
	SWE.1 â€“ Software Safety Requirements Analysis	SWE.6 â€“ Software Qualification Testing	The complete software meets all software safety requirements.
	SWE.2 â€“ Software Architecture Design	SWE.5 â€“ Software Integration & Testing	Component structure and interactions behave as architected (interfaces, data/control flow).
	SWE.3 â€“ Software Detailed Design	SWE.4 â€“ Software Unit Verification	Each unit/module implements the detailed design correctly (unit tests, static analysis).
	SWE.4 â€“ Software Unit Implementation	SWE.4 â€“ Software Unit Verification	The coded unit conforms to its design & requirements (coverage, reviews, tests).
		Tip to say in interview:
		â€œSWE.1 â†” SWE.6, SWE.2 â†” SWE.5, SWE.3/4 â†” SWE.4. Each design stage has a corresponding verification stage, ensuring bidirectional traceability from requirement to test case.â€
	
	ğŸ” One-Line Matching Cheat Sheet
		â€¢ Item Definition / HARA / FSC â†’ Functional Safety Validation
		â€¢ TSC / System Architecture â†’ SYS.3 (integration) then SYS.4 (qualification)
		â€¢ SWE.1 (SW requirements) â†’ SWE.6 (SW qualification)
		â€¢ SWE.2 (SW architecture) â†’ SWE.5 (SW integration)
		â€¢ SWE.3 (detailed design) & SWE.4 (implementation) â†’ SWE.4 (unit verification)
	
	ğŸ§  How to Explain This to an Interviewer (Concise Script)
		â€œIn the ISO 26262 V-model, the left side defines and decomposes safety and designâ€”starting from Item Definition, HARA, FSC, down to TSC, System architecture, and software SWE.1â€“SWE.4. The right side verifies each stage: Functional Safety Validation validates concept-level safety goals; SYS.3/SYS.4 verify the system design and technical safety requirements; SWE.6 verifies software meets SW safety requirements; SWE.5 checks architectural integration; and SWE.4 verifies unit implementations against detailed design. This pairing ensures traceability and that every requirement has a corresponding test.â€
	
